Node.Notes: Unusual to have to him after to Abram her husband. Perhaps the first PP indicates Abram as recipient and the second indicates for his benefit.
Literally, "her mistress was despised in her eyes," but most render more actively like "she looked with contempt on her mistress."
Apparently, Abraham allows the mistress-slave-woman relation to be reestablished by giving Sarai the authority to do as she pleases with Hagar.

Node.Label: OC
Node.Notes: The verb "to hear" forms the nucleus of the name Ishmael.

Apparently used in the OT as a figure of an individualistic lifestyle untrammeled by social convention (Jer 2:24; Hos 8:9), here predictive of Ishmael's future destiny of enjoying a free-roaming, bedouinlike existence.
Uncertain. Could be in the sense of separated from or of living as an enemy of his relatives.
Apparently 3ms verb is indefinite: one calls.
Well name, "well of the Living One who sees me," associated with the name Hagar gave God in 16:13.
